statement.p:
A calculus student spends nearly all of their time thinking about functions 

    f : (a,b) \to \mathbb{R}

where (a,b)  is some interval in \mathbb{R} . Note that, for these functions, the property \bullet in  is precisely the vertical line test for a function.

As it turns out, functions can satisfy none, some or all of the properties in . Indeed, consider the following list of functions:

                 f_1 : \mathbb{R} \amp \to \mathbb{R} \amp f(x) \amp = x^2 \amp \text{neither one-to-one nor onto} 
                 f_2 : \mathbb{N} \amp \to \mathbb{R} \amp f(x) \amp = x \amp \text{one-to-one but not onto} 
                 f_3 : \mathbb{R} \amp \to \mathbb{R} \amp f(x) \amp = x^3 - x \amp \text{onto but not one-to-one} 
                 f_4 : \mathbb{R} \amp \to \mathbb{R} \amp f(x) \amp = x^3 \amp \text{one-to-one and onto} = \text{one-to-one correspondence}
